        <!-- Linear Function Content -->
        <div id="linear" class="function-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <a href="#" class="btn back-btn" onclick="showSection('home')">Back to Home</a>
                <h1>Linear Function Transformation and Domain Explanation</h1>

                <h3>3. Transformation Explanation</h3>
                <p>
                    The function <span class="math">y = 0.5x + 5</span> models the design of a children's straight slide.  
                    Starting from the parent function <span class="math">y = x</span>, which has a slope of 1 and represents a 45° incline,  
                    two key transformations are applied to achieve a safe and realistic model suitable for young children.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Slope Adjustment (Reducing Steepness):</b> The slope is reduced from 1 to 0.5, meaning that for every unit of horizontal movement,  
                    the vertical change is only half as much. This vertical compression reduces the angle of inclination from 45° to approximately 26.56°,  
                    creating a gentler slope that meets safety standards for children's slides, ensuring controlled speed and safety during descent.</li>
                    <li><b>Intercept Setting (Starting Height):</b> The y-intercept is set at 5 (in decimeters), which raises the entire function upward by 5 units.  
                    This represents the starting height of the slide at 5 dm, a height that allows easy access for children while maintaining enjoyable sliding dynamics  
                    suitable for ages 3–6.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    These transformations together yield a practical slide model that reflects the essential characteristics of a safe, smooth, and fun playground design.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Domain and Range Explanation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Domain:</b> The horizontal length of the slide must remain within a safe and comfortable range for children.  
                    Therefore, <span class="math">x ∈ [0, 20]</span> (in decimeters) represents the slide's total horizontal distance of 20 dm,  
                    covering the full sliding path from top to bottom.</li>
                    <li><b>Range:</b> From <span class="math">y = 0.5x + 5</span>, when <span class="math">x = 0</span>, <span class="math">y = 5</span> (the starting height);  
                    and when <span class="math">x = 20</span>, <span class="math">y = 15</span> (the end height, near ground level).  
                    Thus, the range is <span class="math">y ∈ [5, 15]</span> (in decimeters), which ensures a sufficient height difference while keeping the slide's end safely close to the ground.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    The function <span class="math">y = 0.5x + 5</span> accurately models the gentle incline of a children's straight slide, combining appropriate slope and height to meet safety and enjoyment requirements.
                </p>

                <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/mj6suiw0iq?embed" width="500" height="500" style="border: 1px solid #ccc" frameborder=0></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Quadratic Function Content -->
        <div id="quadratic" class="function-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <a href="#" class="btn back-btn" onclick="showSection('home')">Back to Home</a>
                <h1>Quadratic Function Transformation and Domain Explanation</h1>

                <h3>3. Transformation Explanation</h3>
                <p>
                    The given function is \( y = (x - 0.1)^2 - 1.5 \).  
                    It is derived from the parent quadratic function \( f(x) = x^2 \) through straightforward translations that reposition the parabola while maintaining its fundamental shape.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Horizontal Shift (0.1 units right):</b> The parabola is shifted 0.1 units to the right, moving the vertex from \( (0, 0) \) to \( (0.1, -1.5) \).</li>
                    <li><b>Vertical Shift (-1.5 units):</b> The entire graph is shifted downward by 1.5 units, establishing the new minimum value at \( -1.5 \).</li>
                    <li><b>No Stretching/Compression:</b> The coefficient of 1 on the squared term indicates no vertical stretching or compression, preserving the standard parabola shape.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    These simple translations create a parabola with the same opening direction and width as the parent function, but positioned to pass through specific points as required by the modeling context.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Domain and Range Explanation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Domain:</b> Quadratic functions are defined for all real numbers, so the domain is \( (-\infty, +\infty) \).</li>
                    <li><b>Range:</b> Since the squared term \( (x - 0.1)^2 \) has a minimum value of 0 at \( x = 0.1 \),  
                    the function reaches its minimum value of \( -1.5 \) and increases without bound, giving the range \( [-1.5, +\infty) \).</li>
                </ul>

                <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/tz4j7dxyw5?embed" width="500" height="500" frameborder="0"></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Cubic Function Content -->
        <div id="cubic" class="function-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <a href="#" class="btn back-btn" onclick="showSection('home')">Back to Home</a>
                <h1>Cubic Function Transformation and Domain Explanation</h1>

                <h3>3. Transformation Explanation</h3>
                <p>
                    The given cubic function is <span class="math">h(x) = 0.01x³ - 0.12x² + 2</span>.  
                    This function is derived from the parent cubic function <span class="math">f(x) = x³</span> through a series of transformations:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>A vertical compression by a factor of <span class="math">0.01</span>, which reduces the steepness of the curve.</li>
                    <li>A horizontal stretch due to the small coefficient of <span class="math">x³</span>, making the graph wider and smoother.</li>
                    <li>A vertical translation upward by <span class="math">2</span> units, raising the entire curve above the x-axis.</li>
                    <li>The negative quadratic term <span class="math">-0.12x²</span> slightly modifies the symmetry of the curve, creating a smoother hill-like shape.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    Together, these transformations produce a realistic cubic curve that can model gradual rises and falls,  
                    such as the path of a roller coaster or ramp.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Domain and Range Explanation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Domain:</b> Since a cubic function is defined for all real numbers,  
                    the domain of <span class="math">h(x)</span> is <span class="math">(-∞, ∞)</span>.</li>
                    <li><b>Range:</b> Likewise, a cubic function can take all real values depending on <span class="math">x</span>,  
                    so the range of <span class="math">h(x)</span> is also <span class="math">(-∞, ∞)</span>.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    On the graph, the curve rises from the lower left and falls slightly before increasing again,  
                    consistent with the general behavior of a cubic function that has a small coefficient and a mild local minimum and maximum.
                </p>

                <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/dgojg7sger?embed" width="500" height="500" frameborder="0"></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Exponential Function Content -->
        <div id="exponential" class="function-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <a href="#" class="btn back-btn" onclick="showSection('home')">Back to Home</a>
                <h1>Exponential Function Transformation and Domain Explanation</h1>

                <h3>3. Transformation Explanation</h3>
                <p>
                    The given function is \( y = 2^{1.8(x - 1.8)} - 1.7 \).  
                    It is derived from the parent exponential function \( f(x) = 2^x \) through transformations that modify both its growth characteristics and position.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Horizontal Shift (1.8 units right):</b> The function is shifted 1.8 units to the right, moving the characteristic point from \( (0, 1) \) to \( (1.8, -0.7) \).</li>
                    <li><b>Horizontal Stretch (factor \( \frac{1}{1.8} \approx 0.556 \)):</b> The coefficient 1.8 in the exponent stretches the function horizontally by a factor of \( \frac{1}{1.8} \approx 0.556 \), slowing the growth rate.</li>
                    <li><b>Vertical Shift (-1.7 units):</b> The entire graph is shifted downward by 1.7 units, establishing a horizontal asymptote at \( y = -1.7 \) instead of \( y = 0 \).</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    These transformations preserve the fundamental exponential growth pattern while adjusting both the rate of growth and the function's vertical position.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Domain and Range Explanation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Domain:</b> Exponential functions are defined for all real numbers, so the domain is \( (-\infty, +\infty) \).</li>
                    <li><b>Range:</b> Since \( 2^{1.8(x - 1.8)} > 0 \) for all \( x \), subtracting 1.7 gives  
                    \( y > -1.7 \), resulting in the range \( (-1.7, +\infty) \).</li>
                </ul>

                <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/ou9ilxv7xi?embed" width="500" height="500" frameborder="0"></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Logarithmic Function Content -->
        <div id="logarithmic" class="function-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <a href="#" class="btn back-btn" onclick="showSection('home')">Back to Home</a>
                <h1>Logarithmic Function Transformation and Domain Explanation</h1>

                <h3>3. Transformation Explanation</h3>
                <p>
                    The given logarithmic function is <span class="math">h(x) = log(2x) + 1</span>.  
                    It is derived from the parent function <span class="math">f(x) = log(x)</span> through two core transformations to fit the height characteristics of an observation staircase.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Horizontal Compression (factor 2):</b> Replacing <span class="math">x</span> with <span class="math">2x</span> compresses the graph horizontally, causing the function to increase more rapidly within the interval <span class="math">[1, 8]</span>.  
                    This adjustment ensures that the height rises significantly over the observed horizontal distance, avoiding the slow growth of the original logarithmic curve.</li>
                    <li><b>Vertical Shift (+1):</b> The entire graph is shifted upward by one unit, changing the starting height from <span class="math">f(1) = 0</span> to <span class="math">h(1) = 1</span>.  
                    This modification guarantees that all height values remain above ground level, aligning with the actual elevation profile of the observation staircase.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    These transformations make the function <span class="math">h(x)</span> a realistic model of a staircase that gradually rises with a gentle slope, always staying above ground.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Domain and Range Explanation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Domain:</b> Based on the staircase's horizontal span, the domain is defined as <span class="math">[1, 8]</span> meters.  
                    This interval covers the entire horizontal distance from the starting point to the end of the structure, while satisfying the logarithmic requirement <span class="math">x > 0</span>.</li>
                    <li><b>Range:</b> On the interval <span class="math">[1, 8]</span>, the function <span class="math">h(x)</span> is monotonically increasing.  
                    The minimum value is <span class="math">h(1) = 1</span> and the maximum value is approximately <span class="math">h(8) ≈ 2.4</span>, giving the range <span class="math">[1, 2.4]</span>.  
                    This corresponds to the actual height variation of the observation staircase.</li>
                </ul>

                <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/5y8w2nnoem?embed" width="500" height="500" frameborder="0"></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Inverse Proportional Function Content -->
        <div id="inverse" class="function-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <a href="#" class="btn back-btn" onclick="showSection('home')">Back to Home</a>
                <h1>Inverse Proportional Function Transformation and Domain Explanation</h1>

                <h3>3. Transformation Explanation</h3>
                <p>
                    For the parent function <span class="math">f(x) = 1/x</span>, only a vertical stretch transformation is applied.
                    The coefficient is changed from 1 to 10, enlarging the vertical scale of the graph.
                    This transformation directly matches the actual size parameters of the slide:
                    When <span class="math">x = 2</span> (the horizontal position of point A at the platform edge),
                    <span class="math">g(2) = 10/2 = 5</span>, corresponding to a height of 5 meters above the water surface.
                    When <span class="math">x = 5</span> (the horizontal position of point B at the connection point),
                    <span class="math">g(5) = 10/5 = 2</span>, corresponding to a height of 2 meters.
                    No additional horizontal shift is needed, which fits the actual position of the slide intuitively.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Domain and Range Explanation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Domain:</b> Based on the actual horizontal span of the slide segment AB, 
                    from the platform edge (<span class="math">x = 2</span>) to the junction point (<span class="math">x = 5</span>),
                    the interval is continuous and does not involve the asymptote at <span class="math">x = 0</span>.
                    Therefore, the domain can be expressed as <span class="math">[2, 5]</span>.</li>
                    <li><b>Range:</b> Since <span class="math">g(x) = 10/x</span> is a monotonically decreasing function on 
                    <span class="math">[2, 5]</span>, the height smoothly decreases from 5 meters to 2 meters,
                    consistent with the actual shape of the slide. Thus, the range is also 
                    <span class="math">[2, 5]</span>.</li>
                </ul>

                <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/pujvqngqe2?embed" width="500" height="500" frameborder="0"></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Reciprocal Quadratic Function Content -->
        <div id="reciprocal-quadratic" class="function-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <a href="#" class="btn back-btn" onclick="showSection('home')">Back to Home</a>
                <h1>Reciprocal Quadratic Function Transformation and Domain Explanation</h1>

                <h3>3. Transformation Explanation</h3>
                <p>
                    The given function is \( y = \frac{1}{0.3(x - 0.3)^2} - 2.1 \).  
                    It is derived from the parent reciprocal quadratic function \( f(x) = \frac{1}{x^2} \) through several transformations that create a distinctive U-shaped structure with a vertical asymptote.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Horizontal Shift (0.3 units right):</b> The function is shifted 0.3 units to the right, moving the vertical asymptote from \( x = 0 \) to \( x = 0.3 \).</li>
                    <li><b>Vertical Stretch (factor \( \frac{1}{0.3} \approx 3.333 \)):</b> The coefficient \( \frac{1}{0.3} \approx 3.333 \) vertically stretches the graph, making the U-shape narrower and steeper.</li>
                    <li><b>Vertical Shift (-2.1 units):</b> The entire graph is shifted downward by 2.1 units, establishing a horizontal asymptote at \( y = -2.1 \).</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    These transformations create a function with dramatic value changes near the vertical asymptote at \( x = 0.3 \), while approaching \( y = -2.1 \) as \( x \) moves away from the asymptote.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Domain and Range Explanation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Domain:</b> Due to the denominator \( 0.3(x - 0.3)^2 \) becoming zero at \( x = 0.3 \), this point is excluded from the domain.  
                    The domain is \( (-\infty, 0.3) \cup (0.3, +\infty) \).</li>
                    <li><b>Range:</b> Since the squared reciprocal term is always positive and approaches infinity near the asymptote,  
                    the function values are always greater than \( -2.1 \), giving the range \( (-2.1, +\infty) \).</li>
                </ul>

                <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/f7v4hwejc1?embed" width="500" height="500" frameborder="0"></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Cosine Function Content -->
        <div id="cosine" class="function-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <a href="#" class="btn back-btn" onclick="showSection('home')">Back to Home</a>
                <h1>Cosine Function Transformation and Domain Explanation</h1>

                <h3>3. Transformation Explanation</h3>
                <p>
                    The given function is <span class="math">h(t) = 2cos(0.5t) + 3</span>.  
                    It is derived from the parent cosine function <span class="math">f(t) = cos(t)</span> through three targeted transformations to model the swinging motion of a pirate ship ride.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Vertical Stretch (factor 2):</b> The parent function's range of <span class="math">[-1, 1]</span> is stretched to <span class="math">[-2, 2]</span>, enlarging the amplitude.  
                    This matches the real-life height difference between the lowest point (1 m) and highest point (5 m) of the pirate ship's swing.</li>
                    <li><b>Vertical Shift (+3):</b> The graph is moved upward by 3 units, changing the range from <span class="math">[-2, 2]</span> to <span class="math">[1, 5]</span>.  
                    This ensures that all height values remain positive—consistent with the real physical motion of the ship above the water or ground level.</li>
                    <li><b>Horizontal Stretch (factor 0.5):</b> Multiplying <span class="math">t</span> by 0.5 doubles the period from <span class="math">2π</span> to <span class="math">4π</span> (about 12.5 seconds).  
                    This matches the actual timing of the ride, where the pirate ship completes one full swing in approximately 12.5 seconds.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    These combined transformations make <span class="math">h(t)</span> a realistic model of a swinging pirate ship, capturing both the height oscillation and timing accurately.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Domain and Range Explanation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Domain:</b> Considering the actual duration of the motion (about 37.7 seconds in the recorded video),  
                    the domain is chosen as <span class="math">[0, 12π]</span> seconds. This covers six complete oscillation cycles of the pirate ship, representing the entire motion without redundancy.</li>
                    <li><b>Range:</b> From <span class="math">h(t) = 2cos(0.5t) + 3</span>, since <span class="math">cos(0.5t) ∈ [-1, 1]</span>,  
                    the resulting range is <span class="math">h(t) ∈ [1, 5]</span> meters. This matches the real height variation of the pirate ship—lowest at 1 m and highest at 5 m.</li>
                </ul>

                <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/t1w6joiiye?embed" width="500" height="500" frameborder="0"></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Tangent Function Content -->
        <div id="tangent" class="function-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <a href="#" class="btn back-btn" onclick="showSection('home')">Back to Home</a>
                <h1>Tangent Function Transformation and Domain Explanation</h1>

                <h3>3. Transformation Explanation</h3>
                <p>
                    The given function is \( y = 4 \tan(x + 2.1) \).  
                    It is derived from the parent tangent function \( f(x) = \tan(x) \) through transformations that modify both the amplitude and phase of the periodic pattern.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Horizontal Shift (2.1 units left):</b> The function is shifted 2.1 units to the left, changing the phase of the periodic pattern and the positions of the vertical asymptotes.</li>
                    <li><b>Vertical Stretch (factor 4):</b> The coefficient 4 vertically stretches the graph, increasing the steepness of the tangent curves between asymptotes.</li>
                    <li><b>Period Preservation:</b> The period remains \( \pi \) since there is no horizontal stretching/compression factor applied to \( x \) inside the tangent function.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    These transformations create a tangent function with the same fundamental periodicity but with increased amplitude and shifted phase, making the transitions between negative and positive infinity steeper.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Domain and Range Explanation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Domain:</b> The tangent function has vertical asymptotes where \( x + 2.1 = \frac{\pi}{2} + k\pi \) for any integer \( k \).  
                    Therefore, the domain excludes these points: \( x \neq \frac{\pi}{2} + k\pi - 2.1 \).</li>
                    <li><b>Range:</b> The tangent function covers all real numbers, and vertical stretching does not change this characteristic.  
                    The range is \( (-\infty, +\infty) \).</li>
                </ul>

